div.p:
In a imple Mucle, becaue either one Tendon or both ought to be attracted, and becaue the attracting part is thin, and broad, the Belly of the Mucle doth require for its frame, a diverity of Fibres to anwer to the variety of its Figures; whereas Compound Mucles are ditinguihed by their greater variety of Fibres: for beides this variety of Figures which ought to be oberved; o alo ought their Venters, being either more or les, with their order of Fibres, and diverity
of Frames have a repect allowed them. Therefore hall we find that to every imple, as well as compound Mucle is bequeathed a Membranous covering,Membrane inveted with Flehy Fibres for its direct motion, and is intertext with tranvere Fibres for forming it into a Membrane.Vein and Artery. It hath a Vein and Artery inerted into its middle, ending forth of their Surcules into the oblique moving Fibres, from whence the maller Ramifications being dipered through the Intertitia of the Flehes, doth beprinkle and bedew them with their Afflux of Blood,Nerve. and its Reflux: The Nerve entring herein doth ditribute of its mall Branches into its neighbouring Mucles, carrying in it the oul of the commanded action, and commanding its execution in the lower guard of the Flehy Fibres, and of its Membranous Fibrilla's; And as touching its action,Its action. in diection of living Bodies, we plainly perceive that it doth contract, but not as the old opinion held: that the Fibres did contract from their ends, towards their Originations, one end of the Mucle being carried through the other; whereas the Flehy Fibres only, and their ends are een to be contracted towards their middle, their Tendons being mutable, and not altered either in their longitude or thicknes, the which Worthy Steno firt oberved, the which he doth decribe in the Diaphragma, and thoe Mucles appointed for Repiration, the which is moved by a contant turn, as is cleared and perceived; How oft therefore the Mucle is een to be contracted, all its Flehy Fibres in either end are apparently hewn to be driven together, and as it were een to bow and yield to each other; and hence do eem to appear either horter or thicker: the which being looned from its contriction, you will find it to appear in its proper length and thicknes, this alteration being produced by the Spirit or ubtile Matter which paeth from the Tendons into the Flehy parts;
and here tuffing them or filling them up in every place, doth force and compel them to yield hereunto, it tumefying its Fibres; but when this receeds from thee Flehly parts into the Tendons, thee Fibres do leen of their bulk, and do appear in their genuine length and thicknes.

                  Vealius, Adernaus, and Columbus do all decribe them (though
badly) to arie from the beginning of the Right Mucles;
But that thee are ditinct Mucles are evidently apparent.
